The tradeoff managers must consider when dealing with waiting lines would be whether to have multiple lines with multiple servers, one line with one server, one line with multiple servers.  After running a simulation through the computer, I found that the probabilty people will wait 8 minutes in a line with one server, is MUCH less likely, than people waiting in line for 8 minutes when there are mulitple servers.  To me, this makes sense, because although the wait time is the same, people feel that they will be helped quicker when there are more people working.  

It was important to find this information, because now a manager knows what their customers best want, and how long they would be willing to wait in certain types of situtions.  Again, a simulation model imitates a real life situation, which is exactly what this model did. The costs inccured would be for the labor, and fixed costs. The final objective is to find a high probability of when people will wait in line for what they are ordering.  The company wants to profit maximize, and cost minimize ideallly.  So finding the right combination to reach the highest number of customers would be the best.

#7. Explain the concept of Safety Stock.  What is it? Why is it important?

Safety Stock is the inventory that is left over at the time when new inventory arrives.  It could be considered a buffer, because it is essentially left over inventory.  It is important because if the inventory that arrived was forecasted wrong, the company has left over materials to make ends meet.  The thing to be careful about is not to hold onto too much inventory.  The key word is in the term itself, SAFETY.  It helps protect the company by being the extra inventory.
